"1400","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","Cannock, Cannock Chase, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salway","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Somerset and Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Salewi</i>, <i>Selawy</i>, probably from Old English <i>Sǣlwīg</i> (<i>sǣl</i> ‘happiness, prosperity’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘battle’). The name may sometimes have been confused with   Selwyn  .","Americanized form of French   Salois  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Selway","meanings":["English (Somerset and Devon): variant of   Salway  ."]},{"name":"Soloway","meanings":["English: variant of   Salway  .","Americanized form of Jewish, Ukrainian, or Belorussian   Solovey   ‘nightingale’."]},{"name":"Selwyn","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire):","from the Middle English personal name <i>Selewin(e)</i> (Old English <i>Selewine</i>, perhaps from <i>sele</i> ‘hall’ or <i>sǣl</i> ‘happiness, prosperity’ + <i>wine</i> ‘friend’).","of Norman origin, perhaps from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Selvein</i>, <i>Silvein</i> (from Latin <i>Silvanus</i>, an adjective from <i>silva</i> ‘woodland’), with vocalization of /v/ to /w/, possibly through influence of the name above. In Anglo-Norman usage both <i>Selvein</i> and <i>Silvester</i> were sometimes Latinized as <i>Salvagius</i> ‘wild, savage’ (see   Sylvester   and   Savage  ), though whether the vernacular surnames were ever interchangeable is a question for further research."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Adam Salway was born in 1330, in Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Salway, was 30 and his mother, Joan Mytton, was 28. He married Mrs. Robert Adam Salway in 1355, in Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1400, in his hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1330–1400":"1330–1400","1335–1400":"1335–1400","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1302–Female":"1302–Surnud","Abt 1360":"1360","1335":"1335","1302":"1302","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","Cannock, Cannock Chase, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1330–1400":"1330–1400","1335–1400":"1335–1400","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","1360